#text(weight: "bold")[Riot Games — R&D, Gameplay Engineering] \
Re: Software Engineer, Gameplay

#v(10pt)

Dear Riot Games Hiring Team,

I'm excited to apply for the Software Engineer, Gameplay role on your R&D team. Riot's commitment to deep craft in gameplay — and to engineers who raise the bar for everyone around them — is exactly the environment where I do my best work. Over the past four-plus years I've shipped games end-to-end and led gameplay features from the first requirement to the final implementation, and I'd love to bring that to an exciting new Riot title.

At buho Interactive, I lead gameplay development on commercial titles including #text(weight: "bold")[Braverse] (a CookieRun IP project with Devsisters) and #text(weight: "bold")[Wacky Boat]. I work directly with designers to turn product needs into technical designs and shipped features, and I partner with design and art leads to find the bottlenecks slowing the team down — then build the tools that remove them. One example: a Fastlane- and Discord-bot-driven CI/CD pipeline that cut our release-prep time by about 70%, letting QA and design iterate far faster. I care as much about the team's velocity and the engineering standards we hold as I do about the feature in front of me.

Before that, I founded an independent studio and shipped #text(weight: "bold")[Soul of Butterflies – Incubation] to a commercial release on Steam — owning the gameplay systems, puzzle and level design, and engineering, and running the full prototyping and pre-production cycle myself. That taught me to turn ambiguous goals into robust, performant systems under real constraints, and to make pragmatic technical calls with the player's experience as the north star. I'm strong in C\# and Unity, comfortable in C++, and at home with the design patterns and debugging discipline that gameplay work demands.

I'd welcome the chance to help shape the technical vision for a new Riot game, and to show what excellent engineering looks like alongside a team that cares about players as much as I do. Thank you for your consideration.

#v(8pt)
Sincerely,
#v(3pt)
#text(weight: "bold")[Xue Aaron]
